Tapwater vs. Chaudfontaine

A double-blind taste test. On Thursday, December 21, 2023, we [EJ Wagenmakers and Frantisek Bartos] conducted a double-blind taste test among 92 Research Master students and staff members of the Psychology Department at the University of Amsterdam. Each participant tasted two glasses of water, poured from a container "A" and a container "B," and then had to indicate for each glass separately via an online Qualtrics questionnaire how good the water tasted, on a scale from 0 ("would avoid in daily life") through 50 ("neutral") to 100 ("fantastic"). Participants knew that one container held Amsterdam tap water, and the other Chaudfontaine. A colleague had previously determined by tossing a coin that container B was the one with Chaudfontaine; we were informed of the container contents only after the testing had been completed. The experiment was approved by the ethics committee.

Earlier studies. Although blind taste tests of tap water versus mineral water are conducted with some regularity, we are only aware of a handful of studies that have been conducted and reported according to establish scientific procedure. These studies (in Ireland: Wells, 2005; in France: Teillet et al., 2010; in Germany: Debbeler et al., 2018) have found that consumers are generally unable to distinguish tap water from mineral water. Still, we did not want to write off Chaudfontaine completely.

Variables. Below is an explanation of each of the variables in the data set.

years_in_NL: "How many years have you lived in the Netherlands?"

bottled_preference: "Do you prefer tap vs. bottled water in daily life?" [0 = extreme preference for tap water; 5 = no preference; 10 = extreme preference for bottled water]

expected_taste_tap: "What is your prior expectation of the tastiness of the tap water?" [0 = would avoid in daily life; 50 = neutral; 100 = fantastic]

expected_taste_bottled: "What is your prior expectation of the tastiness of the bottled water?" [0 = would avoid in daily life; 50 = neutral; 100 = fantastic]

taste_cup_A_tapwater: "What is the tastiness of the water in cup A?" [0 = would avoid in daily life; 50 = neutral; 100 = fantastic]

taste_cup_B_Chaudfontaine: "What is the tastiness of the water in cup B?" [0 = would avoid in daily life; 50 = neutral; 100 = fantastic]

first_cup: "Which cup did you taste first?" [cup A, cup B]

guess_tap: "Which cup do you think contained the tap water?" [cup A, cup B]

PreferChaudfontaine: A computed column, where "1" indicates that a participant preferred the cup Chaudfontaine over the cup tap water, "0" indicates that a participant rated both equally tasty, and "-1" indicates that a participant preferred the cup tap water over the cup Chaudfontaine.

Analysis. We first used a filter to remove two participants who gave one of the waters a score of 0, as this likely reflects a Qualtrics glitch. We then examine how many people rated the two waters equally (these participants most likely failed to taste any difference). Next we analyse only those participants who indicated the waters were not equally tasty. Below is a series of analyses, the conclusion of which is that more data are needed to make strong statements.

References

Debbeler, L. J., Gamp, M., Blumenschein, M., Keim, D., & Renner, B. (2018). Polarized but illusory beliefs about tap and bottled water: A product- and consumer-oriented survey and blind tasting experiment. Science of The Total Environment, 643, 1400-1410.

Teillet, E., Urbano, C., Cordelle, S., & Schlich, P. (2010). Consumer perception and preference of bottled and tap water. Journal of Sensory Studies, 25, 463-480.

Wells, D. L. (2005). The identification and perception of bottled water. Perception, 34, 1291-1292.

Out of 90 participants who assigned both waters a non-zero score, 90-65=25 (﻿﻿ 28%) deemed them equally tasty. Below we focus our anlyses on those 65 participants who assigned the waters a different score.

Out of 65 participants who expressed a preference, 39 (=60%) preferred the cup Chaudfontaine, and 26 (=40%) preferred the cup tap water.

We will now test this difference against chance, first using a frequentist test and then using a Bayesian test.

Classical Binomial Test

Binomial Test
Variable Level Counts Total Proportion p
PreferChaudfontaine -1 26 65 0.400 0.136
  1 39 65 0.600 0.136
Note.  Proportions tested against value: 0.5.

The proportion of people who prefer Chaudfontaine does not differ significantly from chance.

Two-Sided Bayesian Binomial Test

Bayesian Binomial Test
  Level Counts Total Proportion BF₀₁
PreferChaudfontaine -1 26 65 0.400 1.794
  1 39 65 0.600 1.794
Note.  Proportions tested against value: 0.5. The shape of the prior distribution under the alternative hypothesis is specified by Beta(1, 1).

Prior and Posterior

PreferChaudfontaine - 1

A default test shows that the data are almost twice as likely under H0 than under H1. This level of evidence is weak. Also, if a true effect would be present, there is substantial uncertainty about its size. Finally, the test is two-sided, and it may be argued that the R&D unit of Chaudfontaine would want to advocate the more daring hypothesis that Chaudfontaine tastes better than tap water.

A default one-sided test shows that the data are almost equally likely under H0 and under H1. Also, if a true effect would be present, there is substantial uncertainty about its size. More informed prior distributions may be proposed, but ideally by those who have not yet been in contact with the data. Classical Paired Samples T-Test

The analysis below compares the mean tastiness ratings for the two cups. As is apparent from the table, the p-value equals .047, a result statistically significant at the ﻿﻿ level. Hence, a classical analysis might tempt one into "rejecting the null hypothesis" and concluding that those participants who taste a difference have a preference for Chaudfontaine. Note that the sample effect size is small, with high uncertainty about its population value.

Paired Samples T-Test
95% CI for Cohen's d
Measure 1   Measure 2 t df p Cohen's d SE Cohen's d Lower Upper
taste_cup_B_Chaudfontaine - taste_cup_A_tapwater 2.022 64 0.047 0.251 0.149 0.003 0.497
Note.  Student's t-test.

Two-Sided Bayesian Paired Samples T-Test

The two-sided default Bayesian t-tests yields virtually no difference for or against the rival hypothesis. The results echo the one-sided Bayesian test for proportions presented above, also in terms of the pattern of evidential flow as the data accumulate.

Prior and Posterior
Sequential Analysis

The sequential analysis shows how the evidence changes as the data accumulate. Initially, the data increasingly support the null hypothesis. After about 45 participants, however, the evidence decreases and ultimaltely it ends almost exactly at its starting position: a Bayes factor of 1, which indicates that the data do not change the plausibility of the rival hypotheses at all.

One-Sided Bayesian Paired Samples T-Test

The one-sided default Bayesian t-tests shows that the data are almost twice as likely under H+ than under H0. This is weak evidence;

Vohs One-Sided Bayesian Paired Samples T-Test

The evidence for the alternative hypothesis will be largest if we adopt a prior distribution that is in line with what the sample shows, that is, a small effect in favor of Chaudfontaine. To showcase this, and to assess the robustness of our conclusions, we now execute an analysis with the "Vohs prior" (Vohs et al., 2021), that is, ﻿﻿ , where the plus sign indicates that the normal distribution has been truncated to have mass only on the positive real line.

Prior and Posterior

The result yields a Bayes factor of about 4.7 against H0. With H+ and H0 equally likely a priori, this evidence would move the probability for H+ from 0.50 up to 4.7/5.7 ﻿﻿ 0.82, leaving a probability of 0.18 for H0. We do not believe this level of evidence warrants strong conclusions. More data are needed.
